ern Ireland Assembly|6th Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|8|90|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{steady}}\n|{{steady}}5th\n|72,717\t\n|9.1%\n|style=\"background-color:#CCFFCC\" | '''DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in-UUP-SDLP-Alliance'''\n|}\n\n==Leaders of Alliance==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Leader\n! From\n! To\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 1\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Oliver Napier]] and [[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1970\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 2\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Phelim O'Neill, 2nd Baron Rathcavan|Phelim O'Neill]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 3\n| Oliver Napier\n| 1972\n| 1984\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 4\n| [[John Cushnahan]]\n| 1984\n| 1987\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 5\n| [[John Alderdice]]\n| 1987\n| 1998\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 6\n| [[Se\u00e1n Neeson]]\n| 1998\n| 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 7\n| [[David Ford]]\n| 2001 \n| 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 8\n| [[Naomi Long]]\n| 2016 \n| Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Deputy leaders==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Deputy Leader\n! From\n! To\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 1\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1973\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1976\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 2\n| [[Basil Glass]]\n| 1976\n| 1980\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 3\n| [[David Cook (Northern Ireland politician)|David Cook]]\n| 1980\n| 1984\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 4\n| [[Addie Morrow]]\n| 1984\n| 1987\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 5\n| [[Gordon Mawhinney]]\n| 1987\n| 1991\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 6\n| [[Seamus Close]]\n| 1991\n| 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 7\n| [[Eileen Bell]]\n| 2001\n| 2006\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 8\n| [[Naomi Long]]\n| 2006\n| 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 9\n| [[Stephen Farry]]\n| 2016\n| Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Elected representatives and party spokespeople==\n\n===MPs===\n* [[Stratton Mills]] \u2014 Belfast North, 1973\u201374 (defected from Ulster Unionists)\n* [[Naomi Long]] \u2014 Belfast East, 2010\u20132015\n* [[Stephen Farry]] \u2014 North Down, 2019-present\n\n===MLAs===\n\nElected in the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election]]:\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:97%\"\n|-\n! MP Name !! Constituency\n! Spokesperson for\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Naomi Long]] MLA\n|[[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]]\n| '''Leader of the Alliance Party'''<br />|[[Northern Ireland Executive Office]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Kellie Armstrong]] MLA\n|[[Strangford (Assembly constituency)|Strangford]]\n| [[Department for Infrastructure (Northern Ireland)|Infrastructure]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Paula Bradshaw]] MLA\n|[[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]\n| [[Department of Health (Northern Ireland)|Health]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Stewart Dickson]] MLA\n|[[East Antrim (Assembly constituency)|East Antrim]]\n| [[Justice]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| [[Andrew Muir (politician)|Andrew Muir]]<sup>*</sup> MLA\n| [[North Down (Assembly constituency)|North Down]]\n|[[Department for the Economy|Economy]]<br />[[Department of Finance (Northern Ireland)|Finance]], [[Brexit]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[John Blair (Northern Ireland politician)|John Blair]]<sup>*</sup> MLA\n|[[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]\n| [[Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs|Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Chris Lyttle]] MLA\n|[[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]]\n| [[Department of Education (Northern Ireland)|Education]]\n|}\n\n<sup>*</sup>Blair was co-opted to replace David Ford in July 2018.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44625829 John Blair to become first openly gay MLA at Stormont], BBC News, 27 June 2018</ref> Andrew Muir was co-opted to replace Stephen Farry in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/andrew-muir-selected-as-alliance-partys-new-north-down-mla-38797391.html|title=Andrew Muir selected as Alliance Party's new North Down MLA|work=belfasttelegraph|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Alliance Youth ==\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n| name= Alliance Youth\n| native_name= \n| colorcode= #F7D241\n| logo= [[File:Alliance Youth Banner (B&Y).png|220px|Alliance Youth banner]]\n| chairperson = Hannah Irwin\n| co-chairperson =\n| vice-chairperson = Ciara Campbell\n| secretary2 = Scott Moore\n| founded= 2004\n| headquarters = 88 University Street,<br />[[Belfast]] BT7 1HE,<br />[[Northern Ireland]]\n| membership  =\n| ideology = [[Liberalism]]<ref name=\"BBC News\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Wolfram Nordsieck |url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/nireland.html |title=Parties and Elections in Europe |publisher=Parties-and-elections.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref><br />[[pro-Europeanism]] \n| mother party= Alliance Party\n| international =\n| website = [http://allianceyouthni.org allianceyouthni.org]\n}}\nAlliance Youth is the youth and student movement of the Alliance Party. Alliance members who are under 31 years old automatically become members of Alliance Youth if they choose to share their details at registration. Alliance Youth is also responsible for overseeing Alliance Societies at Northern Ireland universities. [[Young Liberals (UK)|Young Liberals]] Northern Ireland does not organise in any of Northern Ireland's Universities, encouraging members to become active within Alliance Youth societies.\n\n===Activity===\nAlliance Youth actively campaign on issues affecting young people, and aim to shape policy of the main party in these areas. Previous campaigns have focused on racism, child poverty, and human trafficking, as well as specific domestic issues facing young people, such as mental health care, tuition fees, [[sustainable transport]], LGBT rights and homelessness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allianceyouthni.wordpress.com/about/ |title=About Alliance Youth |publisher=Alliance Youth |accessdate=28 November 2015 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Executive===\nThe current executive is as follows:<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.facebook.com/AllianceYouthni/info/?tab=page_info |title=About Alliance Youth |publisher=Alliance Youth |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Position\n!Holder\n|-\n|Chair\n|Hannah Irwin\n|-\n|Vice Chair\n|Ciara Campbell\n|-\n|Secretary\n|Scott Moore\n|-\n|Treasurer\n|Ross Connolly\n|-\n|Campaigns & Development Officer\n|Sarah-Frances Kirk\n|-\n|Equality, Diversity & Welfare Officer\n|Gemma Hughes\n|-\n|Under 18 Membership Officer\n|Luke Patterson \n|-\n|Policy Officer\n|Rowan Fitton\n|-\n|[[Queen's University Belfast|QUB]] Alliance Chair\n|Sarah Frances Kirk (acting)\n|-\n|[[Ulster University|UU]] Alliance Chair\n|Shannon Kelly\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contributions to liberal theory]]\n*[[Demographics and politics of Northern Ireland]]\n*[[Liberalism in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Alliance Party}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{ELDR member parties}}\n{{British political parties}}\n{{Political parties in Northern Ireland}}\n{{European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party}}\n{{United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum, 2011}}}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance Party of Northern Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political party in Northern Ireland}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n|logo          = [[File:Alliance Party of Northern Ireland logo.svg|frameless|upright=1.1|Logo]]\n|colorcode     = {{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}\n|founded       = 21 April 1970\n|ideology      = [[Liberalism]]<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/events/northern_ireland/parties/70610.stm |title=Parties &#124; Northern Ireland Political Parties |publisher=BBC News |date=1998-10-14 |accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Northern Ireland/UK|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/nireland.html|year=2017|accessdate=28 September 2018|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck}}</ref><ref name=\"Deacon2012\"/><br />[[Nonsectarianism]]<ref>{{cite web|author=British Broadcasting Corporation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/recent/troubles/fact_files.shtml?ff=pp01 |title=History \u2013 NI: The Troubles \u2013 Fact Files |publisher=BBC |date=2014-09-18 |accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/alliance-party |title=Alliance party |publisher=Politics.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref><br />[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Brendan Hughes|url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/2016/02/22/news/eu-referendum-where-Northern-Ireland-parties-stand-425039/| title= EU referendum: Where Northern Ireland parties stand|publisher=Irish News|date=2016-02-22|accessdate=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n|predecessor = [[Ulster Liberal Party]]<br />[[New Ulster Movement]]\n|headquarters  =  88 University Street <br> [[Belfast]] <br> BT7 1HE\n|website       = {{official URL}}\n|country       = Northern Ireland\n|name          = Alliance Party of Northern Ireland\n|leader1_title = Leader\n|leader1_name  = [[Naomi Long]]\n|leader2_title = Deputy Leader\n|leader2_name   = [[Stephen Farry]] \n|leader3_title = President\n|leader3_name  = Cllr Geraldine Mulveena\n|leader4_title = Chairperson\n|leader4_name  = Ald Stephen Martin\n|leader5_title = General Secretary\n|founder       = [[Oliver Napier]]<br />[[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]]\n|position      = [[Centrism|Centre]]<ref name=\"Cochrane2014\"/>\n|international = [[Liberal International]]\n|european      = [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] <small>(associate)</small>\n|affiliation1_title = Sister party\n|affiliation1  = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Sister Parties |url=https://www.libdems.org.uk/sister_parties |website=Liberal Democrats |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n|youth_wing    = [[Alliance Youth]]\n|wing2_title = LGBT wing\n|wing2 = Alliance LGBT+\n|colours       = {{Color box|#F6CB2F|border=darkgray}} Yellow<br />{{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}} Black\n|seats1_title  = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]<br />[[List of parliamentary constituencies in Northern Ireland|(NI Seats)]]\n|seats1        = {{Composition bar|1|18|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats2_title  = [[House of Lords of the United Kingdom|House of Lords]]{{efn|Former party leader [[John Alderdice, Baron Alderdice|John Alderdice]] sits in the House of Lords with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].}}\n|seats2        = {{Composition bar|0|791|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats3_title  = [[Northern Ireland Assembly|NI Assembly]]\n|seats3        = {{Composition bar|7|90|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats4_title  = [[Local government in Northern Ireland]]<ref name=\"localcouncil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.opencouncildata.co.uk/index.php|title=Local Council Political Compositions|date=7 January 2018|publisher=Open Council Date UK|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n|seats4        = {{Composition bar|53|462|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n}}\nThe '''Alliance Party of Northern Ireland''' ('''APNI''') is a [[Liberalism|liberal]]<ref name=\"Deacon2012\">{{cite book|author=Russell Deacon|title=Devolution in the United Kingdom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IWo3BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA186|year=2012|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-6973-8|page=186}}</ref> and [[Centrism|centrist]]<ref name=\"Cochrane2014\">{{cite book|author=Feargal Cochrane|chapter=The Future of the Union II: Northern Ireland|editor1=Justin Fisher|editor2=David Denver|editor3=John Benyon|title=Central Debates in British Politics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ST2gBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA54|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-87494-2|page=54}}</ref> [[list of political parties in Northern Ireland|political party in Northern Ireland]]. It was long Northern Ireland's fifth-largest party, currently holding eight seats in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]], but made breakthroughs in recent elections to place third in first preference votes in both the most recent [[European Parliament]] and [[2019 UK general election|United Kingdom general election]]. The party won one of the three Northern Ireland seats in the [[European Parliament]], and one seat, [[North Down (UK Parliament constituency)|North Down]] in the House of Commons respectively.\n\nFounded in 1970 from the [[New Ulster Movement]], the Alliance Party originally represented moderate and non-sectarian [[Unionism in Ireland|unionism]].  However, over time, particularly in the 1990s, it moved towards neutrality on the [[Act of Union (1800)|Union]], and has come to represent wider liberal and non-sectarian concerns. It opposes the [[consociationalism|consociational]] power-sharing mandated by the [[Good Friday Agreement]] as deepening the [[Sectarianism|sectarian]] divide, and, in the Northern Ireland Assembly, it is [[Cross-community vote|designated]] as neither unionist nor [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]], but 'Other'.\n\nIn  [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election in May 2010]] the Alliance Party won their first [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] seat in a UK-wide general election, in the [[Belfast East (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast East]] constituency, unseating [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]], [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]] and leader of the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP). [[Naomi Long]] was the first MP from the Alliance Party since [[Stratton Mills]], who joined the party from the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) in 1973. However, the DUP regained the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] following an electoral pact with the UUP, leaving the Alliance Party with no representation in the House of Commons. In the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Alliance regained its foothold in the House of Commons, with [[Stephen Farry]] winning the North Down seat vacated by independent unionist, [[Sylvia Hermon]]. Earlier that year, leader and former MP, [[Naomi Long]] won the party's first seat in the European Parliament in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European elections]].\n\nThe Alliance Party is a member of the [[Liberal International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberal-international.org/site/Full_Members.html|title=Liberal International: Full Members|publisher=Liberal International|accessdate=3 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525043836/http://www.liberal-international.org/site/Full_Members.html|archivedate=25 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aldeparty.eu/members/member-parties|title=ALDE Party - Member Parties|website=ALDE Party}}</ref> and is aligned with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in [[Great Britain]].<ref name=\"Driver2011\">{{cite book|author=Stephen Driver|title=Understanding British Party Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2_Qq6RJr6_QC&pg=PA125|year=2011|publisher=Polity|isbn=978-0-7456-4077-8|page=125}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early growth and the 1974 Northern Ireland Executive===\nIt was formed in April 1970 as an alternative to the established parties. In the context of a rapidly worsening political crisis, the party aimed not only to present an alternative to what they perceived as [[sectarian]] parties and expressly aimed to act as a bridge between the [[Protestant]] and [[Catholic]] sections of the community and heal the divisions in Northern Ireland society. The Party's founding principles were expressly in favour of Northern Ireland remaining part of the United Kingdom, although in contrast to other [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]] parties, this was expressed in socio-economic rather than [[ethnic group|ethnic]] terms.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loretto |first1=Denis |title=Alliance, Liberals and the SDP |url=https://liberalhistory.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/33-Winter-2001-02.pdf}}</ref>\nOn 5 February 1973, prior to the [[1973 Northern Ireland border poll]], the party's Chairman, [[Jim Hendron]], stated that \"Support for the position of Northern Ireland as an integral part of the United Kingdom is a fundamental principle of the Alliance Party, not only for economic reasons but also because we firmly believe that a peaceful solution to our present tragic problems is only possible within a United Kingdom context. Either a Sinn Fein all-Ireland republic or a [[Vanguard Unionist Progressive Party|Vanguard]]-style Ulster republic would lead to disaster for all our people.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Many errors in poll vote applications |work=[[The News Letter]] |location=Belfast |date=6 February 1973 |page=5}}; {{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Vote in Border Poll-Alliance |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=5 February 1973 |page=3 }}</ref>\n\nThe party's prominence increased in 1972 when three members of the [[Northern Ireland House of Commons]] defected to Alliance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rare voice of moderation during worst of Troubles |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/rare-voice-of-moderation-during-worst-of-troubles-1.596723 |website=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref> The MPs were drawn from across Northern Ireland's political divide and included [[Bertie McConnell]], an independent [[Unionism in the United Kingdom|Unionist]], the [[Ulster Unionist Party|Ulster Unionist]] [[Phelim O'Neill, 2nd Baron Rathcavan|Phelim O\u2019Neill]] and [[Tom Gormley (politician)|Tom Gormley]] who sat as an independent [[Nationalist (Northern Ireland)|Nationalist]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loretto |first1=Denis |title=Alliance, Liberals and Alliance, Liberals and the SDP |journal=Journal of Liberal Democrat History |volume=33 |issue=Winter 2001\u201302 |pages=35 |url=https://liberalhistory.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/33-Loretto-Alliance-Liberals-SDP.pdf}}</ref> In 1973 [[Charles Mulholland, 4th Baron Dunleath | Lord Dunleath]] joined the party in the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web |title=North Belfast 1950-1970 |url=https://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/dnb.htm |website=www.ark.ac.uk}}</ref> [[Stratton Mills]], who had been elected as an [[Ulster Unionist Party|Ulster Unionist]]/[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP at [[Parliament of the United Kingdom | Westminster]] for [[Belfast North (UK Parliament constituency)|North Belfast]] also joined that year, providing the party with its only House of Commons representation until 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction to the Dunleath Papers |url=https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/dunleath.pdf |website=NI Direct |publisher=Public Record Office of Northern Ireland (PRONI)}}</ref> Its first electoral challenge was the [[1973 Northern Ireland local elections|District Council elections of May 1973]] when they managed to win 13.6% of the votes cast.<ref>{{cite web |title=Local Government Elections 1973 |url=https://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/flg73.htm |website=www.ark.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn the elections to the [[Northern Ireland Assembly (1973)|Northern Ireland Assembly]] which followed the [[Sunningdale Agreement]] the party polled 9.2% and won eight seats.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northern Ireland Assembly Elections 1973 |url=https://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/fa73.htm |website=www.ark.ac.uk}}</ref> After the elections Alliance entered the power sharing [[Executive of the 1974 Northern Ireland Assembly| Northern Ireland Executive]]. [[Oliver Napier]] became Legal Minister and Head of the Office of Law Reform and [[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]] took the junior role of Minister for Manpower Services.<ref>{{cite web |title=CAIN: Events: Sunningdale - Members of the 1974 Executive |url=https://cain.ulster.ac.uk/events/sunningdale/executive.htm |website=cain.ulster.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\nAlliance's vote increased significantly in the [[1977 Northern Ireland local elections|1977 local elections]] when it obtained 14.4% of the vote and had 74 Councillors elected.<ref>{{cite web |title=Local Government Elections 1977 |url=https://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/flg77.htm |website=www.ark.ac.uk}}</ref> In 1979, Party Leader [[Oliver Napier]] came closer than Alliance had previously come to electing a Westminster MP, polling just 928 votes short of [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]]'s winning total in [[East Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|East Belfast]], albeit placing third in a three-way marginal.<ref>{{cite web |title=East Belfast 1973-82 |url=https://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/ceb.htm |website=www.ark.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Stabilisation and decline===\nAlliance was seriously damaged by the [[1981 Irish Hunger Strike]], which deeply polarised Northern Ireland politics, and led to the emergence of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] as a serious political force. The party supported the 1985 [[Anglo-Irish Agreement]], and despite claims that this would fatally damage its soft unionist support, Alliance rebounded to pick up 10.0% of the vote in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election]], with some voters rejecting the tacit mainstream unionist support for violence in the aftermath of the Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicholas Whyte|url=http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/gallsum.htm|title=Election results in Northern Ireland since 1973|publisher=Ark.ac.uk|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIts new leader, [[John Alderdice]], polled 32.0% of the vote in [[East Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|East Belfast]], while Alliance came within 15,000 votes of both the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] and Sinn F\u00e9in across Northern Ireland. In 1996 Alderdice accepted a peerage, becoming the Alliance Party\u2019s only representation in Parliament. [[John Alderdice | Lord Alderdice]] took the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] whip on wider UK and European issues but remained free from the whip\u2019s control on issues impacting Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/alderdice-accepts-lib-dem-peerage-in-house-of-lords-1.78580?mode=amp|title=Alderdice accepts Lib Dem peerage in House of Lords|website=www.irishtimes.com|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> \n\nIn 1988, in Alliance's keynote post-Anglo Irish Agreement document, ''Governing with Consent'', Alderdice called for a devolved power-sharing government. Throughout the late 1980s and early 1990s, Alliance's vote stabilised at between 7% and 10%. After the IRA and [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] ceasefires in 1994, Alliance became the first non-nationalist party to enter into talks with Sinn F\u00e9in, as an active participant in the [[Northern Ireland peace process]] negotiations leading to the [[Good Friday Agreement]], which it strongly supported. Alliance polled poorly in the 1996 elections for the [[Northern Ireland Forum]], and the [[1998 Northern Ireland Assembly election|1998 election]] for the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] winning around 6.5% of the vote each time. This did enable the party to win six seats in the Assembly, although this was somewhat of a let-down given that it had been expected to do much better.<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/p1998.htm 1998 elections], ark.ac.uk; accessed 28 May 2016.</ref>\n\n===The Good Friday Agreement era===\n\n====1998\u20132004====\nJohn Alderdice resigned as party leader in 1998 to take up the post of the Assembly's [[Presiding Officer of the Northern Ireland Assembly|Presiding Officer]]. He was replaced by [[Se\u00e1n Neeson]], who himself resigned as party leader in September 2001. Neeson was replaced by [[David Ford]], a member of the Assembly for [[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]].\n<!-- Unsourced image removed: [[File:Alliancemlas2003.jpg|framed|right|The six Alliance MLAs elected in 2003. Rear row left to right: [[Kieran McCarthy]], [[S\u00e9an Neeson]], [[Seamus Close]]. Front row: [[Eileen Bell]], [[David Ford]], [[Naomi Long]].]] -->\n\nIt was predicted that Alliance would suffer electorally as a new centrist challenger established itself in Northern Irish politics, the [[Northern Ireland Women's Coalition]]. Another problem for the APNI was that the rules of the Assembly require major votes (such as the election of the [[First Minister and deputy First Minister]]) to have the support of both a majority of unionist and nationalist MLAs, thus diminishing the importance of parties such as Alliance which are not aligned to either of these two blocs.\n\nIn the [[2003 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2003 Assembly elections]], Alliance held all their seats, while the Women's Coalition lost both of theirs. Alliance's vote fell to just 3.7%. In the [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament Elections in 2004]], Alliance gave strong support to Independent candidate John Gilliland<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allianceparty.org/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120717220437/http://allianceparty.org/article/2004/000371/alliance-endorses-gilliland-for-europe|url-status=dead|title=Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|website=Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|archive-date=17 July 2012|access-date=11 August 2019}}</ref> who polled 6.6% of the vote, the highest for a non-communal candidate in a European election since 1979. In the early years of the peace process, the centre ground was relentlessly squeezed in Northern Ireland politics. The support for Gilliland's candidature, which was also supported by parties such as the [[Workers' Party of Ireland|Workers' Party]] and Northern Ireland Conservatives, reflected a desire to reunite the fragmented and weakened non-communal bloc in Northern Ireland politics.\n\n====2004\u20132016====\n\nIn the 5 May [[2005 United Kingdom general election]], they contested 12 seats and polled 3.9% of the vote. In the simultaneous elections to Northern Ireland's local authorities, they polled 5.0% of first preference votes and had 30 Councillors elected, a gain of two seats relative to the previous elections.\n\nThe 2006\u20132007 period saw some signs of an Alliance upturn, topping the poll and gaining a seat in a by-election for [[Coleraine Borough Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sluggerotoole.com/2006/12/14/alliance-top-poll-in-coleraine/|title=Alliance top poll in Coleraine\u2026|date=14 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2007 Northern Ireland Assembly election]]s, Alliance put in a strong media campaign and polled 5.2%,<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/vote2007/nielection/html/main.stm|title=Northern Ireland election overview|publisher=BBC News|date=13 March 2007|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> up from 3.6% in the previous election and gaining a seat in Belfast South following the successful candidature of [[Anna Lo]], the first ethnic Chinese public representative in a national assembly anywhere in Western Europe. In an election cycle where many pundits had predicted that the Alliance Party would struggle to hold on to the six seats it won in the 2003 election, the party pulled off a credible performance which included Deputy Leader Naomi Long doubling her share of the vote in Belfast East.\n\nIn 2008, during the deadlock between Sinn F\u00e9in and the DUP over the devolution of policing, the two parties came to an agreement that the Minister of Justice would not come from either party. The Alliance Party was the obvious choice but party leader [[David Ford]] said \"it's a very definite and a very emphatic no\". Ford further stated, \"this executive is incompetent, it's time they got on with doing the job that they were set up to do\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/7540963.stm | work=BBC News | title=SF and DUP closer to justice deal | date=4 August 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> Following further negotiations, Ford assumed office on 12 April 2010.\n\nAt the [[European Parliament election, 2009 (United Kingdom)#Northern Ireland|2009 European elections]], Alliance candidate [[Ian Parsley]] achieved the party's best European election vote share in 30 years with 5.5% of the vote.\n\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], the party won its first seat in Westminster, with Naomi Long taking the seat of sitting First Minister [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Sparrow |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/06/uk-election-results-2010-live |title=UK election night 2010 - live coverage |publisher=The Guardian |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2016-08-09}}</ref> The 2011 Northern Ireland Assembly Election resulted in eight Assembly members being returned with a gain in [[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]]. It overtook the UUP on Belfast City Council.\n\nIn a poll conducted in November 2012, Alliance (on 11.6%) overtook the UUP (11.4%) for the first time.<ref>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/alliance-noses-ahead-of-a-flagging-uup-while-the-big-two-consolidate-16244790.html Alliance noses ahead of a flagging UUP while the big two consolidate], by Liam Clarke, ''Belfast Telegraph'', 1 December 2012</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2016 elections to the Assembly]], in spite of initially confident predications from [[David Ford]] that Alliance would see a surplus of up to 11 seats,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2016-36083693 | work =BBC News | title = Northern Ireland election: Alliance Party predicts three-seat gain}}</ref> the party's share of the popular vote stagnated somewhat, from 7.7% in [[2011 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2011]] to 7.0%. Ultimately, its 8 MLAs from their original respective constituencies were returned to Stormont for the fifth Assembly term. Ford later resigned as Alliance Party leader on 6 October 2016, on his 15th anniversary as leader of the party.\n\n=== 2016\u2013present: Opposing Brexit ===\nOn 26 October 2016, [[Naomi Long]] officially became the new leader of the Alliance Party.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-37782400 Naomi Long officially becomes Alliance Party leader], BBC News, 26 October 2016</ref> In the snap [[2017 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2017 Assembly election]], Alliance increased its vote share to 9.1% and retained all eight of their MLA seats in a reduced Assembly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-northern-ireland-2017-39147988|title=DUP and Sinn F\u00e9in largest parties in poll|date=2017-03-04|access-date=2019-08-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> For the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], the party advocated a confirmatory [[referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement]] and remaining in the [[European Single Market]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/allianceparty/pages/3583/attachments/original/1537969137/2017-general-election-manifesto.pdf#page=6 |title=Westminster Manifesto 2017 |author=<!--Not stated--> |year=2017 |website=allianceparty.org |publisher=Sharon Lowry |access-date=2 November 2019 |pages=6, 37}}</ref> In April 2018, the party joined the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party]] as an associate member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aldeparty.eu/news/alliance-party-northern-ireland-joins-alde|title=Alliance Party of Northern Ireland joins ALDE|website=ALDE Party}}</ref>\n\nAlliance increased its vote share by 5 percentage points in the [[2019 Northern Ireland local elections|2019 local elections]] and broke out of its traditional Greater Belfast heartlands by taking seats on [[Armagh City, Banbridge and Craigavon Borough Council|Armagh, Banbridge and Craigavon Borough Council]] and [[Derry City and Strabane District Council|Derry City & Strabane District Council]] where the party had not previously been represented.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-48159710|title=Alliance surge a striking development|last=Devenport|first=Mark|date=2019-05-04|access-date=2019-08-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> During the election campaign, the party had urged a break from \"orange and green politics\" and was vocal in its opposition to [[Brexit]] using the slogan \"Demand Better\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-47966544|title=Alliance urges break from orange and green|last=McCormack|first=Jayne|date=2019-04-17|access-date=2019-08-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European election]], Naomi Long became the Alliance Party's first ever [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], receiving the second of three seats allocated to Northern Ireland and securing the best ever result for Alliance with 18.5% of first-preference votes.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2019/0527/1051976-european-election-northern-ireland/|title=Long makes history as Alliance party take seat in NI|journal=RT\u00c9 News|date=27 May 2019|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref>\n\nThe party greatly increased its vote share at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], from 7.9% to 16.8% of Northern Ireland, over-taking the [[SDLP]] and [[Ulster Unionist Party|UUP]] to come third overall. The party re-gained a seat in the House of Commons ([[North Down (UK Parliament constituency)|North Down]], previously held by the retiring independent [[Sylvia Hermon]]), and was second in another four constituencies.\n\n==Ideology==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2016}}\nOver the past 40 years and particularly since the mid-1990s, Alliance's [[political philosophy]] has veered away from non-sectarian [[Unionism in Ireland|unionism]] towards a more liberal, neutral position on the question of either a [[united Ireland]] or continued Union with Great Britain. While the [[Good Friday Agreement]] has attempted to implement [[Consociational state|consociational power-sharing]], Alliance continues to argue that such enforced coalition government in Northern Ireland entrenches division rather than providing a basis for overcoming it.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nThe Alliance Party was founded on the back of efforts by the [[New Ulster Movement]] (NUM), which was established as a moderating influence upon the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP). After [[Irish nationalist]] politicians withdrew their role as official Opposition at Stormont, and the resignation of UUP [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]] [[Terence O'Neill]] in 1969, the NUM split between those who wished to remain a pressure group for the UUP and those who saw reform only through the establishment of a new political party. The latter broke off and formed the Alliance Party of Northern Ireland on 21 April 1970.\n\nAs Alliance viewed the situation, the major problem of Northern Ireland was the division between Protestant and Catholic. It contended that the turmoil had its origins in that division and not in the [[partition of Ireland]]. \"Partition was the result of the divisions and not the cause of them\". (John Cushnahan, 1979) The party's founding members resolved to change the \"traditional mould\" of sectarian politics in Northern Ireland, by launching a party deliberately set out to win support from both sections of the population. The party's founding principles were an attempt to address the \"fundamental fears\" of Protestants being coerced into a united Ireland, and of Catholics being condemned to a second-class citizenship within Northern Ireland.\n\nThe distinguishing feature of Alliance is its belief in the legitimacy of a distinctive Northern Ireland community, one that has more in common than what divides it, with most inhabitants speaking a common language, sharing some form of Christianity, and not separated by distinguishable racial or physical characteristics. \"Its people are one community living in what has been called a place apart, but sharing a great deal with the rest of this island, the rest of these islands, and the rest of the developed world\". (Alliance 1992) Alliance does not view unionism and nationalism as distinct communities, but as \"political positions\". Furthermore, Alliance sees identity as an individual matter, originating in historical contexts, producing unionist and nationalist traditions. Alliance is at times seen as representing a \"third tradition\". \"In the context of Northern Ireland it includes those who, whether in politics, culture, religion, or in private life have refused to be categorised as Orange or Green\". (Alliance 1992)\n\nAs Alliance have moved to an ideologically liberal perspective, and Northern Ireland society has become more diverse, support for diversity has become a key Alliance platform, with [[Anna Lo]] MLA elected as the first [[Chinese British|ethnically Chinese]] parliamentarian in Western Europe and the party promoting a number of [[openly gay]] spokespeople.\n\n==Electoral performance and the regionalisation of Alliance's vote==\n{{refimprove section|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox political party\t\n|country =\t\n| name = Northern Ireland Council Seats\t\n|native_name = \t\n|colorcode = {{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}\t\n|seats1_title = [[Antrim and Newtownabbey Borough Council|Antrim and Newtownabbey]]\t\n|seats1 = {{Composition bar|7|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\t\n|seats2_title = [[Armagh, Banbridge and Craigavon District Council|Armagh, Banbridge and Craigavon]]\t\n|seats2 = {{Composition bar|3|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\t\n|seats3_title = [[Belfast City Council|Belfast City]]\t\n|seats3 = {{Composition bar|10|60|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats4_title = [[Causeway Coast and Glens District Council|Causeway Coast and Glens]]\t\n|seats4 = {{Composition bar|2|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats5_title = [[Derry and Strabane District Council|Derry and Strabane]]\t\n|seats5 = {{Composition bar|2|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats6_title = [[Fermanagh and Omagh District Council|Fermanagh and Omagh]]\t\n|seats6 = {{Composition bar|1|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats7_title = [[Lisburn and Castlereagh District Council|Lisburn and Castlereagh]]\t\n|seats7 = {{Composition bar|9|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats8_title = [[Mid and East Antrim District Council|Mid and East Antrim]]\t\n|seats8 = {{Composition bar|7|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats9_title = [[Mid Ulster District Council|Mid Ulster]]\t\n|seats9 = {{Composition bar|0|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats10_title = [[Newry, Mourne and Down District Council|Newry, Mourne and Down]]\t\n|seats10 = {{Composition bar|2|41|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n|seats11_title = [[North Down and Ards District Council|North Down and Ards]]\t\n|seats11 = {{Composition bar|10|40|hex=#F6CB2F}}\n}}\n\nOne trend over time with Alliance's vote is that in contrast to 1973, when Alliance support was dispersed across Northern Ireland, Alliance has increasingly polled best in the [[Greater Belfast]] hinterland. For example, the 1977 elections, while representing an overall increase for Alliance, masked a sharp decline in vote share in many Western councils. In the 12 councils covering the former counties of Londonderry, Tyrone, Armagh and Fermanagh their vote only rose in Omagh, it remained static in Magherafelt and fell in the other ten councils (these being Fermanagh, Dungannon, Cookstown, Strabane, Londonderry, Limavady, Coleraine, Newry & Mourne, Armagh and Craigavon.) Overall in these 12 councils the number of Alliance councillors fell from 18 in 1973 to ten in 1977. In contrast, in the rest of the region Alliance increased their number of councillors from 45 to 60.\n\nThe party won eight council seats across Belfast in 1985. Although that has now recovered to six (from three in 2001), the six are entirely from South and East Belfast. Both seats in the Falls Road area of West Belfast were lost after the death and resignation of their councillors there in 1987 while their seat in North Belfast was lost in 1993, regained four years later and lost again in 2001. In the neighbouring areas of Dunmurry Cross (Twinbrook/Dunmurry) and Macedon (Rathcoole) Alliance lost their councillors in 1989 and 1994 respectively; on the other hand, the party won three out of seven seats in Victoria in 2011, the first time since 1977 that the party had won three council seats in the same electoral area.<ref>Alliance won three seats in Belfast Area C and Castlereagh Area B in 1977.</ref>\n\nBy 2005, the party had councillors in only half of Northern Ireland's 18 constituencies. However, this rose to 13 in 2011 after gains in Coleraine, Craigavon, Down and elsewhere. Having had around 30 councillors for a decade, the party won 44 seats in 2011. In the 2010 elections, the Alliance gained the Westminster seat of Belfast East, and gained a 22.6% swing there; in 2011 it re-emphasised that result, winning two out of the six MLA seats available.\n\nIn 2014 the party gained one seat in the Belfast Council area, this coming in North Belfast when Nuala McAllister ousted Sinn F\u00e9in. Outside of the capital the party's vote held up, and with the exception of Patrick Brown winning in Rowallen, there were no outstanding results.\n\nIn the 2015 Westminster elections the party directed their resources at retaining the East Belfast seat Naomi Long had gained from the DUP in 2010. The party lost the seat to the DUP by 2,500 votes, after a Unionist pact, whilst the Alliance vote increased by 6% across the constituency.\n\nThe [[2019 Northern Ireland local elections]] saw a substantial increase in the Alliance vote and resulted in 53 councillors being elected, with the only council not having any Alliance representation is in Mid Ulster. The balance of power in the capital of [[Belfast]], is held by the party after an increase to 10 seats and becoming the 3rd party, at Belfast City Hall.\n\n===Vote share by district council (1973\u20132011)===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! !! 1973 !! 1977 !! 1981 !! 1985 !! 1989 !! 1993 !! 1997 !! 2001 !! 2005 !! 2011 \n|-\n| [[Antrim (borough)|Antrim]] || 16.1 || 16.9 || 10.9 || 7.6 || 7.0 || 8.5 || 8.2 || 5.5 || 6.9 || 11.3 \n|-\n| [[Ards (borough)|Ards]] || 14.8 || 20.8 || 12.3 || 12.4 || 18.8 || 23.4 || 21.1 || 16.7 || 14.1 || 18.2 \n|-\n| [[Armagh City and District Council|Armagh]] || 7.8 || 6.4 || ||  ||  ||  || 0.7 ||  ||  ||  \n|-\n| [[Ballymena (borough)|Ballymena]] || 6.4 || 5.2 ||  ||  |