 Constitutional Convention|1975]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Constitutional Convention|Northern Ireland Constitutional Convention (NICC)]]\n| {{Composition bar|8|78|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n| {{steady}}\n| {{decrease}}5th\n| 64,657\n| 9.8%\n|\n|-\n![[1982 Northern Ireland Assembly election|1982]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 1982|1982 Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|10|78|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}}2\n|{{increase}}4th\n|58,851\n|9.3%\n|\n|-\n![[Northern Ireland Forum|1996]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Forum|Northern Ireland Forum]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|110|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}}7\n|{{decrease}}5th\n|49,176\n|6.5%\n|\n|-\n![[1998 Northern Ireland Assembly election|1998]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 1998|1st Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|6|108|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}}6\n|{{steady}}5th\n|52,636\n|5.6%\n| style=\"background-color:#FFCCCC\" |'''UUP-SDLP-DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in'''\n|-\n![[2003 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2003]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 2003|2nd Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|6|108|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{steady}}6\n|{{steady}}5th\n|25,372\t\n|3.7%\n|style=\"background:salmon;\"|'''Direct Rule'''\n|-\n![[2007 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2007]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 2007|3rd Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|108|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}}1\n|{{steady}}5th\n|36,139\t\n|5.2%\n|style=\"background-color:#CCFFCC\" | '''DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in-UUP-SDLP-Alliance'''\n|-\n![[2011 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2011]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 2011|4th Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|8|108|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}}1\n|{{steady}}5th\n|50,875\t\n|7.7%\n|style=\"background-color:#CCFFCC\" | '''DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in-UUP-SDLP-Alliance'''\n|-\n![[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2016]]\n|[[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly elected in 2016|5th Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|8|108|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{steady}}\n|{{steady}}5th\n|48,447\t\n|7.0%\n| style=\"background-color:#FFCCCC\" |'''DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in-Independent'''\n|-\n![[2017 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2017]]\n|[[Members of the 6th Northern Ireland Assembly|6th Assembly]]\n|{{Composition bar|8|90|hex={{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}}}}\n|{{steady}}\n|{{steady}}5th\n|72,717\t\n|9.1%\n|style=\"background-color:#CCFFCC\" | '''DUP-Sinn F\u00e9in-UUP-SDLP-Alliance'''\n|}\n\n==Leaders of Alliance==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Leader\n! From\n! To\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 1\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Oliver Napier]] and [[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1970\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 2\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Phelim O'Neill, 2nd Baron Rathcavan|Phelim O'Neill]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1972\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 3\n| Oliver Napier\n| 1972\n| 1984\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 4\n| [[John Cushnahan]]\n| 1984\n| 1987\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 5\n| [[John Alderdice]]\n| 1987\n| 1998\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 6\n| [[Se\u00e1n Neeson]]\n| 1998\n| 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 7\n| [[David Ford]]\n| 2001 \n| 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 8\n| [[Naomi Long]]\n| 2016 \n| Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Deputy leaders==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2| Deputy Leader\n! From\n! To\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 1\n| style=\"width:200px;\"| [[Bob Cooper (politician)|Bob Cooper]]\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1973\n| style=\"width:125px;\"| 1976\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 2\n| [[Basil Glass]]\n| 1976\n| 1980\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 3\n| [[David Cook (Northern Ireland politician)|David Cook]]\n| 1980\n| 1984\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 4\n| [[Addie Morrow]]\n| 1984\n| 1987\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 5\n| [[Gordon Mawhinney]]\n| 1987\n| 1991\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 6\n| [[Seamus Close]]\n| 1991\n| 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 7\n| [[Eileen Bell]]\n| 2001\n| 2006\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 8\n| [[Naomi Long]]\n| 2006\n| 2016\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance Party of Northern Ireland/meta/color}};\" | 9\n| [[Stephen Farry]]\n| 2016\n| Incumbent\n|}\n\n==Elected representatives and party spokespeople==\n\n===MPs===\n* [[Stratton Mills]] \u2014 Belfast North, 1973\u201374 (defected from Ulster Unionists)\n* [[Naomi Long]] \u2014 Belfast East, 2010\u20132015\n* [[Stephen Farry]] \u2014 North Down, 2019-present\n\n===MLAs===\n\nElected in the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election]]:\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:97%\"\n|-\n! MP Name !! Constituency\n! Spokesperson for\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Naomi Long]] MLA\n|[[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]]\n| '''Leader of the Alliance Party'''<br />|[[Northern Ireland Executive Office]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Kellie Armstrong]] MLA\n|[[Strangford (Assembly constituency)|Strangford]]\n| [[Department for Infrastructure (Northern Ireland)|Infrastructure]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Paula Bradshaw]] MLA\n|[[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]\n| [[Department of Health (Northern Ireland)|Health]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Stewart Dickson]] MLA\n|[[East Antrim (Assembly constituency)|East Antrim]]\n| [[Justice]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| [[Andrew Muir (politician)|Andrew Muir]]<sup>*</sup> MLA\n| [[North Down (Assembly constituency)|North Down]]\n|[[Department for the Economy|Economy]]<br />[[Department of Finance (Northern Ireland)|Finance]], [[Brexit]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[John Blair (Northern Ireland politician)|John Blair]]<sup>*</sup> MLA\n|[[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]\n| [[Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs|Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs]]\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|[[Chris Lyttle]] MLA\n|[[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]]\n| [[Department of Education (Northern Ireland)|Education]]\n|}\n\n<sup>*</sup>Blair was co-opted to replace David Ford in July 2018.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-politics-44625829 John Blair to become first openly gay MLA at Stormont], BBC News, 27 June 2018</ref> Andrew Muir was co-opted to replace Stephen Farry in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/andrew-muir-selected-as-alliance-partys-new-north-down-mla-38797391.html|title=Andrew Muir selected as Alliance Party's new North Down MLA|work=belfasttelegraph|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Alliance Youth ==\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n| name= Alliance Youth\n| native_name= \n| colorcode= #F7D241\n| logo= [[File:Alliance Youth Banner (B&Y).png|220px|Alliance Youth banner]]\n| chairperson = Hannah Irwin\n| co-chairperson =\n| vice-chairperson = Ciara Campbell\n| secretary2 = Scott Moore\n| founded= 2004\n| headquarters = 88 University Street,<br />[[Belfast]] BT7 1HE,<br />[[Northern Ireland]]\n| membership  =\n| ideology = [[Liberalism]]<ref name=\"BBC News\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Wolfram Nordsieck |url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/nireland.html |title=Parties and Elections in Europe |publisher=Parties-and-elections.eu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref><br />[[pro-Europeanism]] \n| mother party= Alliance Party\n| international =\n| website = [http://allianceyouthni.org allianceyouthni.org]\n}}\nAlliance Youth is the youth and student movement of the Alliance Party. Alliance members who are under 31 years old automatically become members of Alliance Youth if they choose to share their details at registration. Alliance Youth is also responsible for overseeing Alliance Societies at Northern Ireland universities. [[Young Liberals (UK)|Young Liberals]] Northern Ireland does not organise in any of Northern Ireland's Universities, encouraging members to become active within Alliance Youth societies.\n\n===Activity===\nAlliance Youth actively campaign on issues affecting young people, and aim to shape policy of the main party in these areas. Previous campaigns have focused on racism, child poverty, and human trafficking, as well as specific domestic issues facing young people, such as mental health care, tuition fees, [[sustainable transport]], LGBT rights and homelessness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allianceyouthni.wordpress.com/about/ |title=About Alliance Youth |publisher=Alliance Youth |accessdate=28 November 2015 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Executive===\nThe current executive is as follows:<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.facebook.com/AllianceYouthni/info/?tab=page_info |title=About Alliance Youth |publisher=Alliance Youth |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Position\n!Holder\n|-\n|Chair\n|Hannah Irwin\n|-\n|Vice Chair\n|Ciara Campbell\n|-\n|Secretary\n|Scott Moore\n|-\n|Treasurer\n|Ross Connolly\n|-\n|Campaigns & Development Officer\n|Sarah-Frances Kirk\n|-\n|Equality, Diversity & Welfare Officer\n|Gemma Hughes\n|-\n|Under 18 Membership Officer\n|Luke Patterson \n|-\n|Policy Officer\n|Rowan Fitton\n|-\n|[[Queen's University Belfast|QUB]] Alliance Chair\n|Sarah Frances Kirk (acting)\n|-\n|[[Ulster University|UU]] Alliance Chair\n|Shannon Kelly\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contributions to liberal theory]]\n*[[Demographics and politics of Northern Ireland]]\n*[[Liberalism in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Alliance Party}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{ELDR member parties}}\n{{British political parties}}\n{{Political parties in Northern Ireland}}\n{{European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party}}\n{{United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum, 2011}}}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance Party of Northern Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Cbowsie", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alliance_Party_of_Northern_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd", "text_new": "{{Use Harvard referencing|date=May 2019}}\n'''Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0\u025b\u0250\u032f \u02c8n\u0276\u0250\u032f\u02cck\u0252\u02c0|pron}}; born 13 July 1932) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] composer.\n\n== Biography ==\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd was born in [[Gentofte]], Denmark. He studied with [[Vagn Holmboe]] at the [[Royal Danish Academy of Music]] in [[Copenhagen]], and subsequently with [[Nadia Boulanger]] in [[Paris]]. To begin with, he was strongly influenced by the Nordic styles of [[Jean Sibelius]], [[Carl Nielsen]] and [[Vagn Holmboe]]. In the 1960s, N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd began exploring the modernist techniques of central Europe, eventually developing a [[serialism|serial]] compositional system based on the \"infinity series\" {{harv|N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd|1975}}, which he used in his ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'', the Second and Third Symphonies, ''I Ching'', and other works of the late 1960s and 70s {{harv|Mortensen|n.d.(a)}}. Later he became interested in the Swiss artist [[Adolf W\u00f6lfli]], who inspired many of N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's works {{harv|Anon.|n.d.}}, including the Fourth Symphony, the opera ''Det Guddommelige Tivoli'' and ''Papalagi'' for solo guitar.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd has composed works in all major genres: six operas, two ballets, eight symphonies and other pieces for orchestra, several concertos, choral and vocal works, a very large number of chamber works (among them ten string quartets) and several solo instrumental works. These include a number of works for the guitar, mostly written for the Danish guitarist [[Erling M\u00f8ldrup]]: ''In Memory Of...'' (1978), ''Papalagi'' (1981), a series of suites called ''Tales from a Hand'' (1985\u20132001), ''Early Morn'' (1997\u201398) and ''Rondino Amorino'' (1999). One of his most important works for percussion solo is ''I Ching'' (1982) for the Danish percussionist Gert Mortensen. He has also composed music for several films, including ''The Red Cloak'' (1966), ''[[Babette's Feast]]'' (1987), and ''Hamlet, Prince of Denmark'' (1993).\n\nHis eighth symphony was premiered on 19 September 2012 in the [[Helsinki Music Centre]], [[Finland]], by the [[Helsinki Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by [[John Storg\u00e5rds]]. Heikki Valska from the Finnish radio described the symphony as \"very bright and lyrical\" and \"approachable\". It was well received by the audience at the premiere {{harv|Anon.|2012}}.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd is also a prolific writer. He has written many articles dealing with music not only from a technical but also a philosophical viewpoint.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n== Music ==\n[[File:Infinityseries.png|thumb|upright=2|{{listen|plain=yes|filename=Infinityseries.mid|title=Uendelighedsr\u00e6kken in G major (the first 32 terms)}} with numbers=scale steps and 0=A]]\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's music often features the use of the '''infinity series''' ([[Danish language|Danish]] ''Uendelighedsr\u00e6kken'') for [[serialism|serializing]] melody, harmony, and rhythm in musical composition. The method takes its name from the endlessly [[self-similar]] nature of the resulting musical material {{harv|Mortensen|n.d.(b)}}, comparable to [[fractal|fractal geometry]]. Mathematically, the infinity series is an [[integer sequence]]. \"Invented in an attempt to unify in a perfect way repetition and variation,\" {{harv|Sloane}} the first few terms of its simplest form are 0, 1, \u22121, 2, 1, 0, \u22122, 3, \u2026 {{OEIS|A004718}}.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd discovered the melodic infinity series in 1959 and it proved an inspiration for many of his works during the 1960s. However, it was not until his ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'' for small ensemble (1968)\u2014which has been identified as the first \"properly instrumental piece of [[spectral composition]]\" {{harv|Anderson|2000|loc=14}}\u2014and Symphony No. 2 (1970) that it provided the structure for an entire work {{harv|N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd|1975|loc=9}}. The harmonic and rhythmic infinity series were developed in the early 1970s and the three series were first integrated in N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's Symphony No. 3.\n\n== Selected list of works ==\n\n=== Symphonies ===\n* Symphony No. 1 ''Sinfonia austera'' (1953\u201355)\n* Symphony No. 2 (1970)\n* [[Symphony No. 3 (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Symphony No. 3]] (1972\u201375)\n* Symphony No. 4 ''Indian Rose Garden and Chinese Witch's Lake'' (1981)\n* Symphony No. 5 (1990)\n* Symphony No. 6 ''At the End of the Day'' (1998\u201399)\n* Symphony No. 7 (2006)\n* Symphony No. 8 (2011)\n\n=== Concerti ===\n* Concerto for Accordion ''Recall'' (1968)\n* Cello Concerto No. 1 ''Between'' (1985)\n* Cello Concerto No. 2 ''Momentum'' (2009)\n* Harp Concerto No. 1 ''King, Queen and Ace'' (1988)\n* Harp Concerto No. 2 ''through thorns...'' (2003)\n* Piano Concerto ''Concerto in due tempi'' (1994\u201395)\n* Percussion concerto No. 1 ''For a Change'' (1983)\n* Percussion concerto No. 2 ''Bach to the Future'' (1997)\n* Viola Concerto No. 1 ''Remembering Child'' (1986)\n* Violin Concerto No. 1 ''Helle Nacht'' (1986\u201387)\n* Violin Concerto No. 2 ''Borderlines'' (2002)\n\n=== Operas ===\n* ''Labyrinten'' (''The Labyrinth'') (1963)\n* ''[[Gilgamesh (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Gilgamesh]]'' (1972) \n* ''[[Siddhartha (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Siddharta]]'' (1974\u201379)\n* ''[[Der g\u00f6ttliche Tivoli]]'' (''The Divine Circus'') (1983)\n* ''Orfeus: Den uendelige sang'' (''Orpheus: The Endless Song'') (1988)\n* ''[[Nuit des Hommes (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Nuit des Hommes]]'' (1996)\n\n=== Selected other works ===\n* ''Solo Intimo'', Op. 8, for cello (1953)\n* Trio No. 1, Op. 15 (1955) \n* ''Konstellationer'' (''Constellations''), for strings (1958)\n* ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'' (1968)\n* ''Libra'' (1973)\n* ''Turn'', for keyboard (1973)\n* ''Nova genitura'' (1975)\n* ''Wie ein Kind'' (''Like a Child''), for chorus (1979\u201380)\n* ''Dr\u00f8mmesange'' (''Dream Songs'') (1981)\n* ''I Ching'', for solo percussion (1982)\n* ''Najader'' (''The Naiads'') (1986)\n* ''Spaces of Time'' (1991)\n* ''And Time Shall Be No More'', for mixed choir (1994)\n* ''Terrains Vagues'', for orchestra (2000\u20132001)\n\n== Awards ==\n* [[Nordic Council Music Prize]] (1974) for his opera ''Gilgamesh''\n* [[L\u00e9onie Sonning Music Prize]] (1996; Denmark)\n* [[Wihuri Sibelius Prize]] (2006)\n* [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Kravis Prize for New Music]] (2014) {{harv|Kozinn|2014}}\n* [[Ernst von Siemens Music Prize]] (2016)\n\n== References ==\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anon.|n.d.}}|reference=Anon. n.d. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023233442/http://www.pernoergaard.dk/eng/ideer/wolfli3.html |date=October 23, 2007 |title=\"Adolf W\u00f6lffli: W\u00f6lfli's influence\" }}. (from the composer's former website. Accessed 14 May 2010)}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anon.|2012}}|reference=Anon. 2012. {{cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/P2/Artikler/Dagens_P2-historie/2012/09/18102852.htm|title=Ny symfoni af Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd uropf\u00f8rt i Helsinki|publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)]]|date=20 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924034104/http://www.dr.dk/P2/Artikler/Dagens_P2-historie/2012/09/18102852.htm|archivedate=24 September 2012}}}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anderson|2000}}|reference=[[Julian Anderson|Anderson, Julian]]. 2000. \"A Provisional History of Spectral Music.\" ''Contemporary Music Review'' 19, no. 2 (\"Spectral Music History and Techniques\", edited by Joshua Fineberg): 7\u201322.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kozinn|2014}}|reference=[[Allan Kozinn|Kozinn, Allan]]. 2014. \"[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/11/danish-composer-wins-200000-prize-from-philharmonic/ Danish Composer Wins $200,000 Prize from Philharmonic]\". ''[[The New York Times]]'' (11 June): ArtsBeat (accessed 17 December 2014).}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Mortensen|n.d.(a)}}|reference=Mortensen, J\u00f8rgen. n.d.(a) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010091253/http://www.pernoergaard.dk/eng/strukturer/uendelig/uindhold.html |date=October 10, 2007 |title=\"Uendelighedsr\u00e6kken\" }} (The Infinity Series), English version. (accessed 14 May 2010. Formerly on the composer's website, taken off line in November 2007.)}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Mortensen|n.d.(b)}}|reference=Mortensen, J\u00f8rgen. n.d.(b) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20130721064611/http://www.pernoergaard.dk/eng/strukturer/uendelig/uhierarki.html The 'Open Hierarchies' of the Infinity Series]\". Subsection of Mortensen n.d.(a).}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd|1975}}|reference=N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd, Per. 1975. \"Inside a Symphony\". Translated by L. K. Christensen. ''Numus-West'' 2, no. 2:4\u201316.}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Sloane}}|reference={{Cite OEIS|A004718|Infinity sequence}}}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071010091253/http://www.pernoergaard.dk/eng/strukturer/uendelig/uindhold.html The infinity series] \u2013 composer's website \n*[http://unsungsymphonies.blogspot.com/2010/08/master-of-infinite-series-nrgards.html Plain language description of infinity series generation.] (Accessed 15 May 2011)\n*[http://robertinventor.com/ftswiki/Self_Similar_Sloth_Canon_Number_Sequences Mathematical proofs of the results on the composer's website] \u2013 and the connection with other self-similar \"sloth canon\" number sequences\n* {{IMDb name|id=0639168}}\n*[http://www.kb.dk/da/nb/dcm/udgivelser/norgard/vaerkliste.html Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd kompositioner @ www.kb.dk] (Danish)\n\n{{Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd}}\n{{Twelve-tone composers}}\n{{Ernst von Siemens Music Prize}}\n{{Gaudeamus International Composers Award}}\n{{L\u00e9onie Sonning Music Prize laureates}}\n{{Wihuri Sibelius Prize}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norgard, Per}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Twelve-tone and serial composers]]\n[[Category:Composers for the classical guitar]]\n[[Category:Danish opera composers]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:Danish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Danish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Danish Academy of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Gaudeamus Composition Competition prize-winners]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Vagn Holmboe]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Nadia Boulanger]]\n[[Category:Carl Nielsen Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Ernst von Siemens Music Prize winners]]\n[[Category:People from Gentofte Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Harvard referencing|date=May 2019}}\n'''Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0\u025b\u0250\u032f \u02c8n\u0276\u0250\u032f\u02cck\u0252\u02c0|pron}}; born 13 July 1932) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] composer.\n\n== Biography ==\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd was born in [[Gentofte]], Denmark. He studied with [[Vagn Holmboe]] at the [[Royal Danish Academy of Music]] in [[Copenhagen]], and subsequently with [[Nadia Boulanger]] in [[Paris]]. To begin with, he was strongly influenced by the Nordic styles of [[Jean Sibelius]], [[Carl Nielsen]] and [[Vagn Holmboe]]. In the 1960s, N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd began exploring the modernist techniques of central Europe, eventually developing a [[serialism|serial]] compositional system based on the \"infinity series\" {{harv|N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd|1975}}, which he used in his ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'', the Second and Third Symphonies, ''I Ching'', and other works of the late 1960s and 70s {{harv|Mortensen|n.d.(a)}}. Later he became interested in the Swiss artist [[Adolf W\u00f6lfli]], who inspired many of N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's works {{harv|Anon.|n.d.}}, including the Fourth Symphony, the opera ''Det Guddommelige Tivoli'' and ''Papalagi'' for solo guitar.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd has composed works in all major genres: six operas, two ballets, eight symphonies and other pieces for orchestra, several concertos, choral and vocal works, a very large number of chamber works (among them ten string quartets) and several solo instrumental works. These include a number of works for the guitar, mostly written for the Danish guitarist [[Erling M\u00f8ldrup]]: ''In Memory Of...'' (1978), ''Papalagi'' (1981), a series of suites called ''Tales from a Hand'' (1985\u20132001), ''Early Morn'' (1997\u201398) and ''Rondino Amorino'' (1999). One of his most important works for percussion solo is ''I Ching'' (1982) for the Danish percussionist Gert Mortensen. He has also composed music for several films, including ''The Red Cloak'' (1966), ''[[Babette's Feast]]'' (1987), and ''Hamlet, Prince of Denmark'' (1993).\n\nHis eighth symphony was premiered on 19 September 2012 in the [[Helsinki Music Centre]], [[Finland]], by the [[Helsinki Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by [[John Storg\u00e5rds]]. Heikki Valska from the Finnish radio described the symphony as \"very bright and lyrical\" and \"approachable\". It was well received by the audience at the premiere {{harv|Anon.|2012}}.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd is also a prolific writer. He has written many articles dealing with music not only from a technical but also a philosophical viewpoint.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n== Music ==\n[[File:Infinityseries.png|thumb|upright=2|{{listen|plain=yes|filename=Infinityseries.mid|title=Uendelighedsr\u00e6kken in G major (the first 32 terms)}} with numbers=scale steps and 0=A]]\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's music often features the use of the '''infinity series''' ([[Danish language|Danish]] ''Uendelighedsr\u00e6kken'') for [[serialism|serializing]] melody, harmony, and rhythm in musical composition. The method takes its name from the endlessly [[self-similar]] nature of the resulting musical material {{harv|Mortensen|n.d.(b)}}, comparable to [[fractal|fractal geometry]]. Mathematically, the infinity series is an [[integer sequence]]. \"Invented in an attempt to unify in a perfect way repetition and variation,\" {{harv|Sloane}} the first few terms of its simplest form are 0, 1, \u22121, 2, 1, 0, \u22122, 3, \u2026 {{OEIS|A004718}}.\n\nN\u00f8rg\u00e5rd discovered the melodic infinity series in 1959 and it proved an inspiration for many of his works during the 1960s. However, it was not until his ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'' for small ensemble (1968)\u2014which has been identified as the first \"properly instrumental piece of [[spectral composition]]\" {{harv|Anderson|2000|loc=14}}\u2014and Symphony No. 2 (1970) that it provided the structure for an entire work {{harv|N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd|1975|loc=9}}. The harmonic and rhythmic infinity series were developed in the early 1970s and the three series were first integrated in N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd's Symphony No. 3.\n\n== Selected list of works ==\n\n=== Symphonies ===\n* Symphony No. 1 ''Sinfonia austera'' (1953\u201355)\n* Symphony No. 2 (1970)\n* [[Symphony No. 3 (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Symphony No. 3]] (1972\u201375)\n* Symphony No. 4 ''Indian Rose Garden and Chinese Witch's Lake'' (1981)\n* Symphony No. 5 (1990)\n* Symphony No. 6 ''At the End of the Day'' (1998\u201399)\n* Symphony No. 7 (2006)\n* Symphony No. 8 (2011)\n\n=== Concerti ===\n* Concerto for Accordion ''Recall'' (1968)\n* Cello Concerto No. 1 ''Between'' (1985)\n* Cello Concerto No. 2 ''Momentum'' (2009)\n* Harp Concerto No. 1 ''King, Queen and Ace'' (1988)\n* Harp Concerto No. 2 ''through thorns...'' (2003)\n* Piano Concerto ''Concerto in due tempi'' (1994\u201395)\n* Percussion concerto No. 1 ''For a Change'' (1983)\n* Percussion concerto No. 2 ''Bach to the Future'' (1997)\n* Viola Concerto No. 1 ''Remembering Child'' (1986)\n* Violin Concerto No. 1 ''Helle Nacht'' (1986\u201387)\n* Violin Concerto No. 2 ''Borderlines'' (2002)\n\n=== Operas ===\n* ''Labyrinten'' (''The Labyrinth'') (1963)\n* ''[[Gilgamesh (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Gilgamesh]]'' (1972) \n* ''[[Siddhartha (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Siddharta]]'' (1974\u201379)\n* ''[[Der g\u00f6ttliche Tivoli]]'' (''The Divine Circus'') (1983)\n* ''Orfeus: Den uendelige sang'' (''Orpheus: The Endless Song'') (1988)\n* ''[[Nuit des Hommes (N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd)|Nuit des Hommes]]'' (1996)\n\n=== Selected other works ===\n* ''Solo Intimo'', Op. 8, for cello (1953)\n* Trio No. 1, Op. 15 (1955) \n* ''Konstellationer'' (''Constellations''), for strings (1958)\n* ''Voyage into the Golden Screen'' (1968)\n* ''Libra'' (1973)\n* ''Turn'', for keyboard (1973)\n* ''Nova genitura'' (1975)\n* ''Wie ein Kind'' (''Like a Child''), for chorus (1979\u201380)\n* ''Dr\u00f8mmesange'' (''Dream Songs'') (1981)\n* ''I Ching'', for solo percussion (1982)\n* ''Najader'' (''The Naiads'') (1986)\n* ''Spaces of Time'' (1991)\n* ''And Time Shall Be No More'', for mixed choir (1994)\n* ''Terrains Vagues'', for orchestra (2000\u20132001)\n\n== Awards ==\n* [[Nordic Council Music Prize]] (1974) for his opera ''Gilgamesh''\n* [[L\u00e9onie Sonning Music Prize]] (1996; Denmark)\n* [[Wihuri Sibelius Prize]] (2006)\n* [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Kravis Prize for New Music]] (2014) {{harv|Kozinn|2014}}\n* [[Ernst von Siemens Music Prize]] (2016)\n\n== References ==\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anon.|n.d.}}|reference=Anon. n.d. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023233442/http://www.pernoergaard.dk/eng/ideer/wolfli3.html |date=October 23, 2007 |title=\"Adolf W\u00f6lffli: W\u00f6lfli's influence\" }}. (from the composer's former website. Accessed 14 May 2010)}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anon.|2012}}|reference=Anon. 2012. {{cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/P2/Artikler/Dagens_P2-historie/2012/09/18102852.htm|title=Ny symfoni af Per N\u00f8rg\u00e5rd uropf\u00f8rt i Helsinki|publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)]]|date=20 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924034104/http://www.dr.dk/P2/Artikler/Dagens_P2-historie/2012/09/18102852.htm|archivedate=24 September 2012}}}}\n*  {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anderson|2000}}|reference=[[Julian Anderson|Anderson, Julian]]. 2000. \"A Provisional History of Spectral Musi